Analysis of vegetation change in Everglades National Park between 2000 and 2024

(Source: National Park Service, https://www.nps.gov/articles/000/everglades-national-park-south-florida.htm)

The Everglades National Park is a vast subtropical wilderness in southern Florida, where freshwater and saltwater habitats merge to form a rich and diverse ecosystem. The park protects the southern approximaltly tewenty percent of the Everglades in Florida, covering an area of approximatly 1.5 million acres of sawgrass marshes, cypress swamps, hardwood hammokcs, pine rocklands, and extensive mangrove forests (National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior).

Climate change could significantly alter Everglades National Park in a number of ways. For instance, rising sea levels may flood portions of the park and saltwater intrusion could damage frehwater marshes and distub the balance of ecosystems. In addition, more and intense hurricanes could erode shorelines and damage the ecosystem.

In this analysis, we look at possible changes in the Everglades National Park using the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) The NDVI is a measure used to quantify the density and health of vegetation, and values range from -1 to 1 where low values corresponds to rocks or exposed soil and high values indigates greener vegetation, e.g. forests and wetlands.

Dataset

For this analysis, we use NDVI data from NASA's Earth satellites (EARTDATA). To extract the data, the Application for Extracting and Exploring Analysis Ready Samples (AppEEARS) offers a simple and efficient way to do this. The period from 2000 to 2024 was selected for the present analysis. The data for the months April to September was extracted so that the time periods could be flexibly changed and compared later in the investigation.

Below you will find the individual elements of the analysis.

Retrieve NDVI data from 2000 to 2024 for the selected area

In[5]:
# Initialize AppeearsDownloader for MODIS NDVI data
# Set parameters
ndvi_downloader = eaapp.AppeearsDownloader(

    # Give the download a name
    download_key = "everglades_ndvi",

    # Tell it to put the data in the project directory already defined
    project = project,

    # Specify the MODIS product
    product = 'MOD13Q1.061',
    layer = '_250m_16_days_NDVI',

    # Set a start date and end data
    start_date = "04-01",
    end_date = "09-30",

    # Recurring meaning we want to download those dates over multiple years
    recurring = True,

    # Specify the range of years of interest
    year_range = [2000, 2024],

    # Specify the polygon we want to get NDVI data for
    polygon = everglades_gdf
)

Previously, we had a series of individual files, which were more complex to use, especially when searching for time periods or creating time averages. To simplify the work with the NDVI data, we first convert the data into DataArrays and stack the array by time using stack arrays by date using the xr.combine_by_coords() function.

In[9]:
doy_start = -25         # -25 to -22 is the year
doy_end = -18           # -21 to -19 is the day of the year

# Loop through each NDVI image
ndvi_das = []
for ndvi_path in ndvi_paths:

    # Get date from file name
    doy = ndvi_path.name[doy_start:doy_end]
    # doy is a string of year + day of the year 
    date = pd.to_datetime(doy, format="%Y%j")
    # Open dataset

    data = rxr.open_rasterio(ndvi_path, mask_and_scale=True).squeeze()

    # Add date dimension and clean up metadata
    data = data.assign_coords({'date': date})
    data = data.expand_dims({'date': 1})
    data.name = 'NDVI'

    # Prepare for concatenation
    ndvi_das.append(data)
In[10]:
# Combine NDVI images from all dates
ndvi_da = xr.combine_by_coords(ndvi_das, coords = ['date'])

Clacualte and plot difference maps

The next step is to calcualte and plot the differecne in NDVI in our dataset. We split the Dataset in two time periods 2000-2011 and 2012 to 2024. For further analysis, the focus is on the NDVI data for September. On the one hand, it shows the NDVI values after the peak of summer. On the other hand, September is the month with the most tropical storms and hurricanes (see the following figure).

(Source: NOAA, https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/climo/)

No clear NDVI trend, but outliers in individual years

Based on the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI), we looked at Everglades National Park and how the vegetation has changed between 2000 and 2024. The focus was placed on the month of September, following the hottest days of summer and the peak season for tropical storms and hurricanes.

A split of the time series and comparison of the periods 2000 to 2012 and 2013 to 2024 shows that coastal areas and areas adjacent to urban and metropolitan areas of the national park in particular show a decrease in NDVI, while central areas of the park show an increase in NDVI.

The Everglades are extremely low-lying. Thus, even small increase in sea level have a big effect. Saltwater intrusion pushes saltwater farther into freshwater marshes withy the pontential to kill frehswater vegetation. Rising sea levels can also lead to rising groundwater levels in this area, resulting in increased vegetation in the center of the national park.

Looking at the time series, no strong trend is apparent within the time frame of this analysis (perhaps only slightly in the second half). A comparison of the NDVI outside and inside the national park shows higher values inside the park. This is also due to the fact that there is an urban area adjacent to the national park.

When looking at the difference between outside and inside the park, it is interesting to note that there are three years (2005, 2011, and 2017) where the difference is substantial smaller, one of which is particularly pronounced (2017). The year 2017 in particular show a more drastic reduction in the difference compared to the previous and following years. In that year, the hurricane Irma striked the Everglades. Hurricane Irma was a particularly strong and long-lasting event that made landfall as a Category 4 storm on September 10 and then moved northward through Florida and Georgia and did extensive damage to the forest canopy (USGS). The follwing shows the infrared satellite loop from September 10th, 2017, where hurricane Irma hits the Everglades National Park.
